{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01L8c9fRhCm49U84WYsivaFB","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t---\n2\ttitle: ADR-0.7.0-ac020-architectural-lever\n3\tdate: 2026-05-25\n4\ttarget_release: 0.7.0\n5\tdesc: Architectural lever for AC-020 (single-reader concurrency ratio). Compares PCACHE2 / WAL2 / reader-writer pool split / vendor-SQLite swap; recommends one; encodes diagnostic-first stop-rule.\n6\tblast_radius: src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/src/lib.rs (reader pool + sqlite handle layer); src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/Cargo.toml (potentially: libsqlite3-sys version / vendor); src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/tests/perf_gates.rs (AC-020 bound); dev/design/recovery.md (if WAL2 / vendor swap); dev/notes/performance-whitepaper-notes.md (closure narrative)\n7\tstatus: draft, HITL-required\n8\t---\n9\t\n10\t# ADR-0.7.0 — AC-020 architectural lever\n11\t\n12\t**Status:** draft, HITL-required.\n13\t\n14\tThis ADR picks the **one** architectural lever that closes AC-020\n15\tin 0.7.0. AC-020's read-path concurrency ratio (currently 3.530×\n16\tmedian; required ≥ 5.33× per `tests/perf_gates.rs:245`) cannot be\n17\tclosed by canonical-SQLite engine-side levers alone — Pack 5 / 6 /\n18\t6.G exhausted the canonical-SQLite knob surface and falsified each\n19\tone. The residual gap is in code surfaces that canonical SQLite\n20\tdoes not expose (custom page-cache allocator) or that require\n21\tsubstantial architectural change (separate readers from writer at\n22\tthe SQLite layer, or replace SQLite with a derivative).\n23\t\n24\tThe four candidates below are **mutually exclusive** for the 0.7.0\n25\trelease. A second lever fires only if the first underdelivers AND\n26\tHITL re-opens this ADR. Stacking two structural levers in a single\n27\trelease would violate `feedback_reliability_principles` (single\n28\tload-bearing change per release for any high-blast-radius surface).\n29\t\n30\t## Status / context\n31\t\n32\tAC-020 contract (`dev/test-plan.md` § Current Perf Attribution\n33\tL143-190; `src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/tests/perf_gates.rs:211`):\n34\tsingle-reader connection pool of 8 workers must achieve concurrent\n35\tspeedup ≥ 5.33× over the sequential baseline on the AC-020 fixture\n36\t(50 rounds × 4 mixed-vector / FTS / hybrid queries per thread).\n37\t\n38\tCurrent measurement (`dev/notes/performance-whitepaper-notes.md`\n39\t§ 2 and § 12, plus `dev/plans/runs/G3_5-cache-pressure-telemetry-\n40\toutput.json`): seq 563 ms, conc 161 ms, speedup **3.530×** (Pack 6.G\n41\tclose 2026-05-04, aarch64 Tegra dev host). The canonical-runner\n42\tre-measurement of AC-020 has not been taken at 0.6.1 close (only\n43\tAC-012 was re-measured); the diagnostic-first phase below\n44\t(`0.7.0-PERF-DIAG`) captures the AC-020 canonical-runner baseline\n45\tbefore the architectural lever fires.\n46\t\n47\tThe whitepaper notes\n48\t(`dev/notes/performance-whitepaper-notes.md` § 6 hypothesis\n49\thierarchy + § 11 Pack 5 close narrative + § 12 Pack 6 + Pack 6.G\n50\tsynthesis) classify the residual as one of three remaining causes:\n51\t\n52\t1. `pcache1` mutex acquires on every hit-path page-fetch — canonical\n53\t   SQLite cannot eliminate without a custom page-cache allocator.\n54\t2. WAL shared-memory atomics (frame counters, page references,\n55\t   checkpoint sequence) — survive `SQLITE_THREADSAFE=2` because\n56\t   they are not threading-mode mutexes.\n57\t3. rusqlite-side internal Mutex or `ReaderPool::borrow`\n58\t   `Mutex<Vec<Connection>>` — upstream of any SQLite-side flag.\n59\t\n60\tThe diagnostic-first phase below disambiguates which of these\n61\tdominates at canonical scale before the architectural lever\n62\tcommits to its specific blast radius.\n63\t\n64\t## Options compared (four)\n65\t\n66\t### Option 1 — `SQLITE_CONFIG_PCACHE2` custom page-cache allocator\n67\t\n68\t**Mechanism:** install a custom `sqlite3_pcache_methods2` via\n69\t`sqlite3_config(SQLITE_CONFIG_PCACHE2, ...)` at process start\n70\t(before any `sqlite3_initialize()` call, mirroring the B.1\n71\tordering constraint from\n72\t`dev/notes/performance-whitepaper-notes.md` § 5 / § 7.3). Custom\n73\tallocator side-steps the global `pcache1` mutex by providing\n74\tper-handle (or per-reader-pool-slot) page-cache slabs that do not\n75\tcontend.\n76\t\n77\t**Blast radius:** medium. Pure FFI extension on top of canonical\n78\tSQLite; no SQLite version change; no schema impact; no durability\n79\tcontract change. New `pcache2` allocator implementation +\n80\tprocess-start init wiring + per-slot accounting code. Roughly\n81\t~400-600 LOC of unsafe FFI + safe Rust wrapping.\n82\t\n83\t**Expected payoff:** high if § 6 hypothesis #1 (`pcache1` mutex\n84\thit-path contention) is the dominant residual; medium otherwise.\n85\tThe whitepaper's `cache_used` = 3.35% and `delta_miss_rate` =\n86\t0.023% from G.3.5 (page-cache lever falsified at canonical-SQLite\n87\tPRAGMA layer) means the residual is in mutex acquires, not miss\n88\trate — exactly the surface PCACHE2 targets.\n89\t\n90\t**Prerequisite diagnostic (per § 7.1 of the whitepaper, made\n91\tmachine-checkable here):**\n92\t\n93\t- `perf record -g --call-graph dwarf` of the AC-020 binary in\n94\t  sequential and concurrent modes, on the canonical runner.\n95\t- `perf report` aggregator must show `pcache1Fetch` + `pcache1Pin`\n96\t  - their mutex-acquire siblings growing super-linearly under\n97\t    concurrency (concurrent share ≥ 2× sequential share).\n98\t\n99\tIf the diagnostic falsifies this hypothesis (mutex share is in\n100\tWAL atomics or rusqlite-side instead), PCACHE2 is **skipped**\n101\twithout revert; the diagnostic data points at WAL2 or R-W split\n102\tinstead.\n103\t\n104\t**Cross-check against do-not-retry ledger\n105\t(`dev/notes/performance-whitepaper-notes.md` § 5):** ledger\n106\tcontains `sqlite3_config(SQLITE_CONFIG_MULTITHREAD)` (B.1) and\n107\tcompile-time `THREADSAFE=2` (C.1) but **does not contain**\n108\t`SQLITE_CONFIG_PCACHE2`. PCACHE2 is genuinely untried and is\n109\texplicitly listed in whitepaper § 7.5 as a \"per-connection\n110\tlookaside and page cache\" follow-on. **Not on the ledger.**\n111\t\n112\t### Option 2 — WAL2 (SQLite WAL2 patchset)\n113\t\n114\t**Mechanism:** swap the bundled SQLite for the WAL2 fork of\n115\tSQLite (one of the upstream patchsets — see `sqlite.org` WAL2\n116\tbranch). WAL2 maintains two WAL files alternately, allowing\n117\treaders to operate on one while writers move to the other; the\n118\tshared-memory atomics surface contention can be reduced because\n119\treaders do not have to serialize on the same WAL frame counter\n120\tthe writer is incrementing.\n121\t\n122\t**Blast radius:** large. Touches the durability + recovery\n123\tsurface: WAL2 changes the on-disk WAL file layout (two `*-wal`\n124\tfiles instead of one, plus a control file). `dev/design/recovery.md`\n125\tneeds an updated section explaining the multi-file WAL recovery\n126\tshape. The 0.6.0 schema version stays the same (no row-format\n127\tchange) but the WAL-file invariants used by external backup tools\n128\tno longer hold. `libsqlite3-sys` must be replaced with a custom\n129\tbuild or a different crate.\n130\t\n131\t**Expected payoff:** high if § 6 hypothesis #2 (WAL shared-memory\n132\tatomics) is the dominant residual; low otherwise. Pack 5 evidence\n133\t(C.1 REVERT with `mutex_atomic` symbols surviving `THREADSAFE=2`)\n134\tpoints at this hypothesis but did not isolate it from #1 — that\n135\tisolation is the DIAG-slice's job.\n136\t\n137\t**Prerequisite diagnostic:**\n138\t\n139\t- Same `perf record` pass as Option 1.\n140\t- WAL2 is justified only if `walShmGet` / `walReadFrame` mutex\n141\t  acquires (or their aarch64 atomic equivalents\n142\t  `__aarch64_swp4_rel` / `__aarch64_cas4_acq` per whitepaper § 6)\n143\t  show super-linear growth AND PCACHE2's prerequisite is not met.\n144\t\n145\t**Cross-check against do-not-retry ledger:** ledger contains no\n146\tWAL2 entry (Pack 5 / 6 / 6.G did not try it because it was always\n147\tclassified Pack 7 territory per § 13 of the Pack 5 plan and\n148\t§ 14-15 of the whitepaper). **Not on the ledger.**\n149\t\n150\t### Option 3 — Reader / writer physical separation (R-W pool split)\n151\t\n152\t**Mechanism:** replace the current single-database-file shape with\n153\ttwo SQLite handles per logical operation: a writer connection on\n154\tthe canonical DB file, and a reader pool of 8 connections on a\n155\t**read-only snapshot** maintained via SQLite's `sqlite3_snapshot_*`\n156\tAPI or by serving readers from a checkpointed read-replica file.\n157\tReaders and writer no longer contend on the same WAL or page\n158\tcache; the only synchronization is the snapshot-handoff at\n159\tprojection-runtime commit boundaries.\n160\t\n161\t**Blast radius:** large. Changes the writer/reader architecture\n162\tinside `fathomdb-engine`: `lib.rs:158` (`ReaderPool` declaration)\n163\t\n164\t- `lib.rs:707` (constructor) + `lib.rs:773` (pool fill) + the\n165\t  projection-runtime commit path. Touches the snapshot semantics\n166\t  that AC-059b reader-tx snapshot contract relies on\n167\t  (`dev/notes/performance-whitepaper-notes.md` § 4 KEPT entries).\n168\t  Requires a snapshot-freshness ADR (because the snapshot version\n169\t  becomes part of the user-observable correctness contract).\n170\t\n171\t**Expected payoff:** medium-high if § 6 hypothesis #3\n172\t(rusqlite-side / `ReaderPool::borrow` Mutex) is the dominant\n173\tresidual; the borrow Mutex disappears when readers and writer\n174\thold structurally separate handles.\n175\t\n176\t**Prerequisite diagnostic:**\n177\t\n178\t- Same `perf record` pass.\n179\t- R-W split is justified only if Rust-side mutex symbols\n180\t  (`std::sync::Mutex::lock` on the `ReaderPool::borrow` path or\n181\t  rusqlite's internal Mutex) dominate over SQLite-side mutex\n182\t  symbols.\n183\t\n184\t**Cross-check against do-not-retry ledger:** ledger does not\n185\tcontain R-W split. Pack 5 / 6 stayed inside the\n186\tsingle-file-single-pool topology. The closest entry is F.0\n187\t(thread-affine readers; KEPT) which removed the borrow-pool Mutex\n188\ton the dispatch path but kept readers and writer on the same\n189\tdatabase file. **Not on the ledger.**\n190\t\n191\t### Option 4 — Vendor-SQLite swap (libSQL or sqlite3mc)\n192\t\n193\t**Mechanism:** replace canonical SQLite entirely with a vendor\n194\tfork that ships different concurrency primitives. libSQL (Turso's\n195\tfork) ships per-connection page-cache allocators by default and\n196\thas a different WAL implementation. sqlite3mc adds multi-cipher\n197\tsupport but reuses canonical SQLite's concurrency surface — only\n198\tattractive if encryption is also needed.\n199\t\n200\t**Blast radius:** very large. Replaces the SQL engine that the\n201\tentire 0.6.0 design rests on. Affects durability, recovery,\n202\tcrash-safety, extension compatibility (vec0 / FTS5 are SQLite\n203\textensions; libSQL ships these but version-skewed). Changes\n204\tdeployment surface: host-system SQLite paths\n205\t(`dev/notes/performance-whitepaper-notes.md` § 8 cross-references)\n206\tare no longer relevant; commits the project to bundled-only\n207\tdeployment. ADR-class because durability + recovery contracts\n208\tshift.\n209\t\n210\t**Expected payoff:** high but undifferentiated. libSQL claims\n211\tbetter concurrency but Pack 5 / 6 evidence cannot be replayed\n212\tagainst it without doing the swap. Cannot be justified by\n213\tdiagnostic data alone — it's a \"different bottleneck shape\" bet,\n214\tnot a \"this specific mutex\" fix.\n215\t\n216\t**Cross-check against do-not-retry ledger:** ledger does not\n217\tcontain vendor-SQLite swap (Pack 5 / 6 stayed bundled per\n218\tconstraint). **Not on the ledger.**\n219\t\n220\t## Diagnostic-first stop-rule\n221\t\n222\t**Precondition for any of the four levers landing in 0.7.0:** the\n223\t`0.7.0-PERF-DIAG` slice must publish a `perf record` + classified\n224\treport on the canonical runner (`ubuntu-latest` x86_64, AMD EPYC,\n225\t4-core, glibc 2.39, SQLite 3.45.x bundled). The slice's output\n226\tJSON must include:\n227\t\n228\t- Sequential per-symbol cycle aggregate (top 10 frames by share).\n229\t- Concurrent per-symbol cycle aggregate (same top 10 frames + any\n230\t  frame whose concurrent share is > 2× its sequential share).\n231\t- Classification of each super-linear-grower into one of the\n232\t  three hypothesis buckets:\n233\t  - **H1 = pcache1 / page-cache mutex** (PCACHE2 territory).\n234\t  - **H2 = WAL atomics / shm protocol** (WAL2 territory).\n235\t  - **H3 = rusqlite or ReaderPool-borrow Mutex** (R-W split\n236\t    territory).\n237\t- A **single primary hypothesis** call with the cycle-share\n238\t  evidence that supports it.\n239\t\n240\tThe architectural-lever slice does NOT spawn until the DIAG output\n241\tJSON exists and HITL Q2 picks the lever consistent with the DIAG\n242\tprimary hypothesis.\n243\t\n244\tIf DIAG returns no super-linear-grower (concurrent shares within\n245\t1.2× of sequential shares across the top 10 frames), AC-020 may\n246\tbe **closed by re-measurement** — the canonical runner's 4-core\n247\tslice may not exhibit the contention the aarch64 12-core dev host\n248\texhibited. In that case, this ADR is closed `status: locked,\n249\tintervention: none` and AC-074 (the revised AC-020 budget) is\n250\tasserted by the existing harness on the canonical runner without\n251\tany lever landing.\n252\t\n253\t## Recommendation\n254\t\n255\t> **Drafter's recommendation (HITL Q2 picks):**\n256\t>\n257\t> **Option 1 — PCACHE2** as the default lever, contingent on the\n258\t> DIAG slice confirming H1 (page-cache mutex contention) as the\n259\t> primary hypothesis.\n260\t>\n261\t> Fallback ranking if DIAG points elsewhere:\n262\t>\n263\t> - H2 dominant → Option 2 (WAL2).\n264\t> - H3 dominant → Option 3 (R-W split).\n265\t> - DIAG inconclusive AND HITL judges the cycle-share evidence\n266\t>   weighs toward H1 → Option 1 (PCACHE2; the smallest blast\n267\t>   radius among the three structural levers).\n268\t> - DIAG falsifies H1/H2/H3 (no super-linear grower) → no lever;\n269\t>   close by re-measurement per the stop-rule above.\n270\t>\n271\t> Option 4 (vendor-SQLite swap) is **last resort**: justified only\n272\t> if all three single-cause levers underdeliver and HITL re-opens\n273\t> this ADR. It is recorded here for completeness because the\n274\t> whitepaper § 13 lists it; it is not the 0.7.0-default lever.\n275\t\n276\t**Rationale for PCACHE2 as default:**\n277\t\n278\t- Smallest blast radius among the three structural levers (no\n279\t  on-disk format change, no schema impact, no recovery-contract\n280\t  change, no SQLite vendor change).\n281\t- Pack 5 G.3.5 telemetry already implicates `pcache1` mutex\n282\t  acquires (whitepaper § 12: residual `page_cache` 6.29% concurrent\n283\t  share from hit-path page-fetch mutex acquires).\n284\t- Recoverable: if PCACHE2 lands and AC-020 still misses the revised\n285\t  budget by < 1×stddev, HITL can stack a second knob (lookaside\n286\t  sizing already LANDED INCONCLUSIVE at G.1) without re-opening\n287\t  the whole ADR.\n288\t- Independent of the workload: PCACHE2 helps any read-heavy\n289\t  workload that exercises page-cache hit-path concurrency, not\n290\t  just AC-020.\n291\t\n292\t## Rejected alternatives\n293\t\n294\t**R1 — Stack two levers in 0.7.0 (PCACHE2 + WAL2; or any pair).**\n295\tViolates `feedback_reliability_principles` (one load-bearing\n296\tchange per release on a high-blast-radius surface). If lever-1\n297\tunderdelivers, HITL re-opens this ADR after 0.7.0 ships; lever-2\n298\tlands in 0.7.1 or 0.8.0. Stacking would also confound attribution:\n299\tif AC-020 closes with both landed, the project cannot tell which\n300\tone moved the needle, and the next AC-020-class regression has no\n301\thypothesis hierarchy to fall back on.\n302\t\n303\t**R2 — Defer to 0.8.0.** 0.8.0's anchor (knowledge-store +\n304\tretrieval for Memex per `dev/roadmap/0.8.0.md`) consumes the\n305\tretrieval surface that AC-020 gates. Deferring AC-020 either\n306\tblocks 0.8.0 or ships 0.8.0 on a perpetually-RED concurrency gate.\n307\t\n308\t**R3 — Retry a do-not-retry-ledger lever\n309\t(`dev/notes/performance-whitepaper-notes.md` § 5).** Explicitly\n310\tforbidden by the planning prompt and the handoff. The § 5 levers\n311\twere falsified with clean methodology; re-trying them without a\n312\tnew mechanism is a process failure. Any ledger lever that\n313\treappears here must carry an explicit HITL override pointing at\n314\tthe new mechanism — none of the four options above is a ledger\n315\tlever.\n316\t\n317\t**R4 — Lift the AC-020 contract.** Loosening `1.5 /\n318\tAC020_THREADS` to a more achievable ratio is a contract change,\n319\tnot a perf fix. Rejected by the same reasoning as\n320\tADR-0.7.0-text-query-latency-gates-revised § R1: the contract is\n321\tthe user-visible promise, and a project that can only meet its\n322\tcontract by weakening it has not closed the gate.\n323\t\n324\t**R5 — Drop AC-020 (delete the test).** Rejected; the test is the\n325\tload-bearing gate against future regressions on the read-path\n326\tconcurrency surface, which is REQ-053's `search` underlay. The\n327\tproject's reliability principles forbid deleting a load-bearing\n328\tgate to make CI green.\n329\t\n330\t## Acceptance criterion\n331\t\n332\t**AC-074 (proposed, per\n333\t`dev/plans/0.7.0-implementation.md` § Per-AC scoreboard):**\n334\tAC-020 sequential + concurrent + speedup measurements on the\n335\tcanonical runner at the AC-020 fixture meet the revised envelope\n336\trecorded in `ADR-0.7.0-text-query-latency-gates-revised` § AC-020\n337\t**after** the chosen architectural lever lands. If DIAG closes\n338\tthe gate without a lever, AC-074 is asserted by re-measurement\n339\talone (no source change to the engine; the AC-020 test bound\n340\tstays unchanged).\n341\t\n342\tHITL confirms AC-074's wording when locking this ADR. The slice\n343\tthat closes AC-074 (`0.7.0-PERF-AC020`) does not spawn until both\n344\tthis ADR and `ADR-0.7.0-text-query-latency-gates-revised` read\n345\t`status: locked`.\n346\t\n347\t## Consequences\n348\t\n349\t- `dev/plans/0.7.0-implementation.md` § Slice sequence orders\n350\t  PERF-DIAG before PERF-AC020 unconditionally.\n351\t- `dev/notes/performance-whitepaper-notes.md` is updated by the\n352\t  closing slice's docs commit: § 5 ledger gets one new \"kept\" or\n353\t  \"reverted\" entry per the slice's verdict; § 14 gets a closing\n354\t  narrative paragraph.\n355\t- `dev/design/recovery.md` may add a § \"WAL2 layout\" section\n356\t  (Option 2 only) or a § \"Reader snapshot lifecycle\" section\n357\t  (Option 3 only). The closing slice's prompt skeleton enumerates\n358\t  the doc updates per chosen option.\n359\t- `src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/tests/perf_gates.rs:245` bound\n360\t  expression is unchanged; the budget numbers in the test\n361\t  constants section update per the revised-budgets ADR.\n362\t\n363\t## Citations\n364\t\n365\t- HITL 2026-05-24 (release rescope; 0.7.0 → perf-only).\n366\t- HITL Q2 lock (date pending; this ADR draft is the input).\n367\t- `ADR-0.7.0-text-query-latency-gates-revised` (parallel; owns\n368\t  the numeric envelope).\n369\t- `dev/notes/performance-whitepaper-notes.md` § 2 / § 4 / § 5 /\n370\t  § 6 / § 7 / § 11 / § 12 (AC-020 evidence chain).\n371\t- `dev/plans/0.6.0-Phase-9-Pack-5-performance-diagnostics.md`\n372\t  § 13 (Pack 7 proposed work; PCACHE2 / WAL2 / vendor-swap as\n373\t  the next-tier levers).\n374\t- `dev/test-plan.md` § Current Perf Attribution L143-190.\n375\t- `src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/tests/perf_gates.rs:211, 245`.\n376\t- MEMORY: `feedback_reliability_principles` (one load-bearing\n377\t  change per release on a high-blast-radius surface),\n378\t  `feedback_tdd` (RED test asserting the revised budget on the\n379\t  canonical runner before the lever lands).\n380\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"aa315b5f-03de-4674-91e7-1c237d33c95a","uuid":"dcb0c79a-d51f-4658-8bc1-12bf6eea0ea3","timestamp":"2026-05-27T13:11:55.770Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/tmp/fdb-0.7.0-PVQ-S0-20260527T130459Z/dev/adr/ADR-0.7.0-ac020-architectural-lever.md","content":"---\ntitle: ADR-0.7.0-ac020-architectural-lever\ndate: 2026-05-25\ntarget_release: 0.7.0\ndesc: Architectural lever for AC-020 (single-reader concurrency ratio). Compares PCACHE2 / WAL2 / reader-writer pool split / vendor-SQLite swap; recommends one; encodes diagnostic-first stop-rule.\nblast_radius: src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/src/lib.rs (reader pool + sqlite handle layer); src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/Cargo.toml (potentially: libsqlite3-sys version / vendor); src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/tests/perf_gates.rs (AC-020 bound); dev/design/recovery.md (if WAL2 / vendor swap); dev/notes/performance-whitepaper-notes.md (closure narrative)\nstatus: draft, HITL-required\n---\n\n# ADR-0.7.0 — AC-020 architectural lever\n\n**Status:** draft, HITL-required.\n\nThis ADR picks the **one** architectural lever that closes AC-020\nin 0.7.0. AC-020's read-path concurrency ratio (currently 3.530×\nmedian; required ≥ 5.33× per `tests/perf_gates.rs:245`) cannot be\nclosed by canonical-SQLite engine-side levers alone — Pack 5 / 6 /\n6.G exhausted the canonical-SQLite knob surface and falsified each\none. The residual gap is in code surfaces that canonical SQLite\ndoes not expose (custom page-cache allocator) or that require\nsubstantial architectural change (separate readers from writer at\nthe SQLite layer, or replace SQLite with a derivative).\n\nThe four candidates below are **mutually exclusive** for the 0.7.0\nrelease. A second lever fires only if the first underdelivers AND\nHITL re-opens this ADR. Stacking two structural levers in a single\nrelease would violate `feedback_reliability_principles` (single\nload-bearing change per release for any high-blast-radius surface).\n\n## Status / context\n\nAC-020 contract (`dev/test-plan.md` § Current Perf Attribution\nL143-190; `src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/tests/perf_gates.rs:211`):\nsingle-reader connection pool of 8 workers must achieve concurrent\nspeedup ≥ 5.33× over the sequential baseline on the AC-020 fixture\n(50 rounds × 4 mixed-vector / FTS / hybrid queries per thread).\n\nCurrent measurement (`dev/notes/performance-whitepaper-notes.md`\n§ 2 and § 12, plus `dev/plans/runs/G3_5-cache-pressure-telemetry-\noutput.json`): seq 563 ms, conc 161 ms, speedup **3.530×** (Pack 6.G\nclose 2026-05-04, aarch64 Tegra dev host). The canonical-runner\nre-measurement of AC-020 has not been taken at 0.6.1 close (only\nAC-012 was re-measured); the diagnostic-first phase below\n(`0.7.0-PERF-DIAG`) captures the AC-020 canonical-runner baseline\nbefore the architectural lever fires.\n\nThe whitepaper notes\n(`dev/notes/performance-whitepaper-notes.md` § 6 hypothesis\nhierarchy + § 11 Pack 5 close narrative + § 12 Pack 6 + Pack 6.G\nsynthesis) classify the residual as one of three remaining causes:\n\n1. `pcache1` mutex acquires on every hit-path page-fetch — canonical\n   SQLite cannot eliminate without a custom page-cache allocator.\n2. WAL shared-memory atomics (frame counters, page references,\n   checkpoint sequence) — survive `SQLITE_THREADSAFE=2` because\n   they are not threading-mode mutexes.\n3. rusqlite-side internal Mutex or `ReaderPool::borrow`\n   `Mutex<Vec<Connection>>` — upstream of any SQLite-side flag.\n\nThe diagnostic-first phase below disambiguates which of these\ndominates at canonical scale before the architectural lever\ncommits to its specific blast radius.\n\n## Options compared (four)\n\n### Option 1 — `SQLITE_CONFIG_PCACHE2` custom page-cache allocator\n\n**Mechanism:** install a custom `sqlite3_pcache_methods2` via\n`sqlite3_config(SQLITE_CONFIG_PCACHE2, ...)` at process start\n(before any `sqlite3_initialize()` call, mirroring the B.1\nordering constraint from\n`dev/notes/performance-whitepaper-notes.md` § 5 / § 7.3). Custom\nallocator side-steps the global `pcache1` mutex by providing\nper-handle (or per-reader-pool-slot) page-cache slabs that do not\ncontend.\n\n**Blast radius:** medium. Pure FFI extension on top of canonical\nSQLite; no SQLite version change; no schema impact; no durability\ncontract change. New `pcache2` allocator implementation +\nprocess-start init wiring + per-slot accounting code. Roughly\n~400-600 LOC of unsafe FFI + safe Rust wrapping.\n\n**Expected payoff:** high if § 6 hypothesis #1 (`pcache1` mutex\nhit-path contention) is the dominant residual; medium otherwise.\nThe whitepaper's `cache_used` = 3.35% and `delta_miss_rate` =\n0.023% from G.3.5 (page-cache lever falsified at canonical-SQLite\nPRAGMA layer) means the residual is in mutex acquires, not miss\nrate — exactly the surface PCACHE2 targets.\n\n**Prerequisite diagnostic (per § 7.1 of the whitepaper, made\nmachine-checkable here):**\n\n- `perf record -g --call-graph dwarf` of the AC-020 binary in\n  sequential and concurrent modes, on the canonical runner.\n- `perf report` aggregator must show `pcache1Fetch` + `pcache1Pin`\n  - their mutex-acquire siblings growing super-linearly under\n    concurrency (concurrent share ≥ 2× sequential share).\n\nIf the diagnostic falsifies this hypothesis (mutex share is in\nWAL atomics or rusqlite-side instead), PCACHE2 is **skipped**\nwithout revert; the diagnostic data points at WAL2 or R-W split\ninstead.\n\n**Cross-check against do-not-retry ledger\n(`dev/notes/performance-whitepaper-notes.md` § 5):** ledger\ncontains `sqlite3_config(SQLITE_CONFIG_MULTITHREAD)` (B.1) and\ncompile-time `THREADSAFE=2` (C.1) but **does not contain**\n`SQLITE_CONFIG_PCACHE2`. PCACHE2 is genuinely untried and is\nexplicitly listed in whitepaper § 7.5 as a \"per-connection\nlookaside and page cache\" follow-on. **Not on the ledger.**\n\n### Option 2 — WAL2 (SQLite WAL2 patchset)\n\n**Mechanism:** swap the bundled SQLite for the WAL2 fork of\nSQLite (one of the upstream patchsets — see `sqlite.org` WAL2\nbranch). WAL2 maintains two WAL files alternately, allowing\nreaders to operate on one while writers move to the other; the\nshared-memory atomics surface contention can be reduced because\nreaders do not have to serialize on the same WAL frame counter\nthe writer is incrementing.\n\n**Blast radius:** large. Touches the durability + recovery\nsurface: WAL2 changes the on-disk WAL file layout (two `*-wal`\nfiles instead of one, plus a control file). `dev/design/recovery.md`\nneeds an updated section explaining the multi-file WAL recovery\nshape. The 0.6.0 schema version stays the same (no row-format\nchange) but the WAL-file invariants used by external backup tools\nno longer hold. `libsqlite3-sys` must be replaced with a custom\nbuild or a different crate.\n\n**Expected payoff:** high if § 6 hypothesis #2 (WAL shared-memory\natomics) is the dominant residual; low otherwise. Pack 5 evidence\n(C.1 REVERT with `mutex_atomic` symbols surviving `THREADSAFE=2`)\npoints at this hypothesis but did not isolate it from #1 — that\nisolation is the DIAG-slice's job.\n\n**Prerequisite diagnostic:**\n\n- Same `perf record` pass as Option 1.\n- WAL2 is justified only if `walShmGet` / `walReadFrame` mutex\n  acquires (or their aarch64 atomic equivalents\n  `__aarch64_swp4_rel` / `__aarch64_cas4_acq` per whitepaper § 6)\n  show super-linear growth AND PCACHE2's prerequisite is not met.\n\n**Cross-check against do-not-retry ledger:** ledger contains no\nWAL2 entry (Pack 5 / 6 / 6.G did not try it because it was always\nclassified Pack 7 territory per § 13 of the Pack 5 plan and\n§ 14-15 of the whitepaper). **Not on the ledger.**\n\n### Option 3 — Reader / writer physical separation (R-W pool split)\n\n**Mechanism:** replace the current single-database-file shape with\ntwo SQLite handles per logical operation: a writer connection on\nthe canonical DB file, and a reader pool of 8 connections on a\n**read-only snapshot** maintained via SQLite's `sqlite3_snapshot_*`\nAPI or by serving readers from a checkpointed read-replica file.\nReaders and writer no longer contend on the same WAL or page\ncache; the only synchronization is the snapshot-handoff at\nprojection-runtime commit boundaries.\n\n**Blast radius:** large. Changes the writer/reader architecture\ninside `fathomdb-engine`: `lib.rs:158` (`ReaderPool` declaration)\n\n- `lib.rs:707` (constructor) + `lib.rs:773` (pool fill) + the\n  projection-runtime commit path. Touches the snapshot semantics\n  that AC-059b reader-tx snapshot contract relies on\n  (`dev/notes/performance-whitepaper-notes.md` § 4 KEPT entries).\n  Requires a snapshot-freshness ADR (because the snapshot version\n  becomes part of the user-observable correctness contract).\n\n**Expected payoff:** medium-high if § 6 hypothesis #3\n(rusqlite-side / `ReaderPool::borrow` Mutex) is the dominant\nresidual; the borrow Mutex disappears when readers and writer\nhold structurally separate handles.\n\n**Prerequisite diagnostic:**\n\n- Same `perf record` pass.\n- R-W split is justified only if Rust-side mutex symbols\n  (`std::sync::Mutex::lock` on the `ReaderPool::borrow` path or\n  rusqlite's internal Mutex) dominate over SQLite-side mutex\n  symbols.\n\n**Cross-check against do-not-retry ledger:** ledger does not\ncontain R-W split. Pack 5 / 6 stayed inside the\nsingle-file-single-pool topology. The closest entry is F.0\n(thread-affine readers; KEPT) which removed the borrow-pool Mutex\non the dispatch path but kept readers and writer on the same\ndatabase file. **Not on the ledger.**\n\n### Option 4 — Vendor-SQLite swap (libSQL or sqlite3mc)\n\n**Mechanism:** replace canonical SQLite entirely with a vendor\nfork that ships different concurrency primitives. libSQL (Turso's\nfork) ships per-connection page-cache allocators by default and\nhas a different WAL implementation. sqlite3mc adds multi-cipher\nsupport but reuses canonical SQLite's concurrency surface — only\nattractive if encryption is also needed.\n\n**Blast radius:** very large. Replaces the SQL engine that the\nentire 0.6.0 design rests on. Affects durability, recovery,\ncrash-safety, extension compatibility (vec0 / FTS5 are SQLite\nextensions; libSQL ships these but version-skewed). Changes\ndeployment surface: host-system SQLite paths\n(`dev/notes/performance-whitepaper-notes.md` § 8 cross-references)\nare no longer relevant; commits the project to bundled-only\ndeployment. ADR-class because durability + recovery contracts\nshift.\n\n**Expected payoff:** high but undifferentiated. libSQL claims\nbetter concurrency but Pack 5 / 6 evidence cannot be replayed\nagainst it without doing the swap. Cannot be justified by\ndiagnostic data alone — it's a \"different bottleneck shape\" bet,\nnot a \"this specific mutex\" fix.\n\n**Cross-check against do-not-retry ledger:** ledger does not\ncontain vendor-SQLite swap (Pack 5 / 6 stayed bundled per\nconstraint). **Not on the ledger.**\n\n## Diagnostic-first stop-rule\n\n**Precondition for any of the four levers landing in 0.7.0:** the\n`0.7.0-PERF-DIAG` slice must publish a `perf record` + classified\nreport on the canonical runner (`ubuntu-latest` x86_64, AMD EPYC,\n4-core, glibc 2.39, SQLite 3.45.x bundled). The slice's output\nJSON must include:\n\n- Sequential per-symbol cycle aggregate (top 10 frames by share).\n- Concurrent per-symbol cycle aggregate (same top 10 frames + any\n  frame whose concurrent share is > 2× its sequential share).\n- Classification of each super-linear-grower into one of the\n  three hypothesis buckets:\n  - **H1 = pcache1 / page-cache mutex** (PCACHE2 territory).\n  - **H2 = WAL atomics / shm protocol** (WAL2 territory).\n  - **H3 = rusqlite or ReaderPool-borrow Mutex** (R-W split\n    territory).\n- A **single primary hypothesis** call with the cycle-share\n  evidence that supports it.\n\nThe architectural-lever slice does NOT spawn until the DIAG output\nJSON exists and HITL Q2 picks the lever consistent with the DIAG\nprimary hypothesis.\n\nIf DIAG returns no super-linear-grower (concurrent shares within\n1.2× of sequential shares across the top 10 frames), AC-020 may\nbe **closed by re-measurement** — the canonical runner's 4-core\nslice may not exhibit the contention the aarch64 12-core dev host\nexhibited. In that case, this ADR is closed `status: locked,\nintervention: none` and AC-074 (the revised AC-020 budget) is\nasserted by the existing harness on the canonical runner without\nany lever landing.\n\n## Recommendation\n\n> **Drafter's recommendation (HITL Q2 picks):**\n>\n> **Option 1 — PCACHE2** as the default lever, contingent on the\n> DIAG slice confirming H1 (page-cache mutex contention) as the\n> primary hypothesis.\n>\n> Fallback ranking if DIAG points elsewhere:\n>\n> - H2 dominant → Option 2 (WAL2).\n> - H3 dominant → Option 3 (R-W split).\n> - DIAG inconclusive AND HITL judges the cycle-share evidence\n>   weighs toward H1 → Option 1 (PCACHE2; the smallest blast\n>   radius among the three structural levers).\n> - DIAG falsifies H1/H2/H3 (no super-linear grower) → no lever;\n>   close by re-measurement per the stop-rule above.\n>\n> Option 4 (vendor-SQLite swap) is **last resort**: justified only\n> if all three single-cause levers underdeliver and HITL re-opens\n> this ADR. It is recorded here for completeness because the\n> whitepaper § 13 lists it; it is not the 0.7.0-default lever.\n\n**Rationale for PCACHE2 as default:**\n\n- Smallest blast radius among the three structural levers (no\n  on-disk format change, no schema impact, no recovery-contract\n  change, no SQLite vendor change).\n- Pack 5 G.3.5 telemetry already implicates `pcache1` mutex\n  acquires (whitepaper § 12: residual `page_cache` 6.29% concurrent\n  share from hit-path page-fetch mutex acquires).\n- Recoverable: if PCACHE2 lands and AC-020 still misses the revised\n  budget by < 1×stddev, HITL can stack a second knob (lookaside\n  sizing already LANDED INCONCLUSIVE at G.1) without re-opening\n  the whole ADR.\n- Independent of the workload: PCACHE2 helps any read-heavy\n  workload that exercises page-cache hit-path concurrency, not\n  just AC-020.\n\n## Rejected alternatives\n\n**R1 — Stack two levers in 0.7.0 (PCACHE2 + WAL2; or any pair).**\nViolates `feedback_reliability_principles` (one load-bearing\nchange per release on a high-blast-radius surface). If lever-1\nunderdelivers, HITL re-opens this ADR after 0.7.0 ships; lever-2\nlands in 0.7.1 or 0.8.0. Stacking would also confound attribution:\nif AC-020 closes with both landed, the project cannot tell which\none moved the needle, and the next AC-020-class regression has no\nhypothesis hierarchy to fall back on.\n\n**R2 — Defer to 0.8.0.** 0.8.0's anchor (knowledge-store +\nretrieval for Memex per `dev/roadmap/0.8.0.md`) consumes the\nretrieval surface that AC-020 gates. Deferring AC-020 either\nblocks 0.8.0 or ships 0.8.0 on a perpetually-RED concurrency gate.\n\n**R3 — Retry a do-not-retry-ledger lever\n(`dev/notes/performance-whitepaper-notes.md` § 5).** Explicitly\nforbidden by the planning prompt and the handoff. The § 5 levers\nwere falsified with clean methodology; re-trying them without a\nnew mechanism is a process failure. Any ledger lever that\nreappears here must carry an explicit HITL override pointing at\nthe new mechanism — none of the four options above is a ledger\nlever.\n\n**R4 — Lift the AC-020 contract.** Loosening `1.5 /\nAC020_THREADS` to a more achievable ratio is a contract change,\nnot a perf fix. Rejected by the same reasoning as\nADR-0.7.0-text-query-latency-gates-revised § R1: the contract is\nthe user-visible promise, and a project that can only meet its\ncontract by weakening it has not closed the gate.\n\n**R5 — Drop AC-020 (delete the test).** Rejected; the test is the\nload-bearing gate against future regressions on the read-path\nconcurrency surface, which is REQ-053's `search` underlay. The\nproject's reliability principles forbid deleting a load-bearing\ngate to make CI green.\n\n## Acceptance criterion\n\n**AC-074 (proposed, per\n`dev/plans/0.7.0-implementation.md` § Per-AC scoreboard):**\nAC-020 sequential + concurrent + speedup measurements on the\ncanonical runner at the AC-020 fixture meet the revised envelope\nrecorded in `ADR-0.7.0-text-query-latency-gates-revised` § AC-020\n**after** the chosen architectural lever lands. If DIAG closes\nthe gate without a lever, AC-074 is asserted by re-measurement\nalone (no source change to the engine; the AC-020 test bound\nstays unchanged).\n\nHITL confirms AC-074's wording when locking this ADR. The slice\nthat closes AC-074 (`0.7.0-PERF-AC020`) does not spawn until both\nthis ADR and `ADR-0.7.0-text-query-latency-gates-revised` read\n`status: locked`.\n\n## Consequences\n\n- `dev/plans/0.7.0-implementation.md` § Slice sequence orders\n  PERF-DIAG before PERF-AC020 unconditionally.\n- `dev/notes/performance-whitepaper-notes.md` is updated by the\n  closing slice's docs commit: § 5 ledger gets one new \"kept\" or\n  \"reverted\" entry per the slice's verdict; § 14 gets a closing\n  narrative paragraph.\n- `dev/design/recovery.md` may add a § \"WAL2 layout\" section\n  (Option 2 only) or a § \"Reader snapshot lifecycle\" section\n  (Option 3 only). The closing slice's prompt skeleton enumerates\n  the doc updates per chosen option.\n- `src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/tests/perf_gates.rs:245` bound\n  expression is unchanged; the budget numbers in the test\n  constants section update per the revised-budgets ADR.\n\n## Citations\n\n- HITL 2026-05-24 (release rescope; 0.7.0 → perf-only).\n- HITL Q2 lock (date pending; this ADR draft is the input).\n- `ADR-0.7.0-text-query-latency-gates-revised` (parallel; owns\n  the numeric envelope).\n- `dev/notes/performance-whitepaper-notes.md` § 2 / § 4 / § 5 /\n  § 6 / § 7 / § 11 / § 12 (AC-020 evidence chain).\n- `dev/plans/0.6.0-Phase-9-Pack-5-performance-diagnostics.md`\n  § 13 (Pack 7 proposed work; PCACHE2 / WAL2 / vendor-swap as\n  the next-tier levers).\n- `dev/test-plan.md` § Current Perf Attribution L143-190.\n- `src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/tests/perf_gates.rs:211, 245`.\n- MEMORY: `feedback_reliability_principles` (one load-bearing\n  change per release on a high-blast-radius surface),\n  `feedback_tdd` (RED test asserting the revised budget on the\n  canonical runner before the lever lands).\n","numLines":380,"startLine":1,"totalLines":380}}}
